Macedonians vote in a referendum on changing the country's name.
The Macedonian people voted Sunday in a referendum on whether to change its name to the "Republic of North Macedonia", a move that would resolve a decades-old dispute with Greece and block applications for admission to the European Union and NATO.
Greece, which has a province called Macedonia, maintains that the name of its northern neighbors represents a claim to its territory and has vetoed their entry into NATO and the EU.
The governments of the two countries reached an agreement in June on the proposed new name, but nationalist opponents allege that the change would prejudice the ethnic identity of the majority of Macedonia's Slavic population.
President Gjorge Ivanov said he would not vote in the referendum and a boycott campaign raised doubts about whether the result would meet the 50 percent minimum needed for the referendum to be valid.
The question on the ballot paper was: "Are you in favour of NATO and EU membership with the acceptance of the agreement with Greece?"
Proponents of the name change, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, argue that it is a price worth paying to gain admission to entities such as the EU or NATO from Macedonia, one of the countries emerging from the fall of Yugoslavia.
"Today I came to vote for the future of the country, for the youth of Macedonia, so that they can live freely under the protection of the European Union, because this means a safer life for all of us", said Olivera Georgijevska, 79, in Skopje.
Although it is not legally binding, many members of parliament have said they will abide by the result of the vote and make it final.
A change of nine would require a two-thirds majority in the parliament.
The state election commission said that at 1 p.m. there were no irregularities.
However, turnout was only 16 percent, compared to 34 percent in the last parliamentary election in 2016, when 66 percent of registered voters cast their ballots.
"I came to vote for my children, our place is in Europe", said Gjose Tanevski, a 62-year-old voter from the capital Skopje.
Macedonian Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and son Dushko cast their votes for the Macedonian referendum on the country's name change that would pave the way for its accession to the European Union in Strumica, Macedonia, on September 30, 2018.
In front of the parliament in Skopje, Vladimir Kavardarkov, 54, was preparing a small stage and placing chairs in front of the tents set up for those who boycotted the referendum.
"We are in favour of joining NATO and the EU, but we want to do it with our heads held high and not through the service door", Kavadarkov added.
We are a poor country, but we have dignity.
If we are not accepted as Macedonia, we can go to other countries like China and Russia and become part of the Eurasian Union.
Prime Minister Zaev claims that NATO membership will bring much-needed investment to Macedonia, which has an unemployment rate of over 20 percent.
"I think the vast majority will be in favor because more than 80 percent of our citizens are in favor of joining the EU and NATO", Zaev commented after casting his vote.
He said a positive result would be "confirmation of our future".
A poll published last Monday by the Macedonian Institute for Political Research revealed that between 30 and 43 percent of voters would participate in the referendum, a figure that is below the required figure.
Another poll by the Macedonian TV network Telma indicated that 57 percent of those polled planned to go to the polls on Sunday.
Of those, 70 percent said they would vote yes.
For a referendum to be valid, the result must be 50 percent plus one vote.
A failure of the referendum would represent the first major blow to the policy of the pro-Western government since it came to power in May last year.
