Scotland's private schools have a track record of academic excellence, and this continued in 2018 with another collection of outstanding exam results, only reinforced by individual and collective success in sports, art, music and other community subjects.
With over 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best possible education for pupils and their parents.
Private schools aim to prepare their students for higher education, for the career of their choice and their place as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a tailor-made curriculum, we are seeing that modern languages continue to be a popular and desired topic within schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you talk to a man in a language he understands, it goes to his head.
But if you talk to him in his own language, it goes to his heart.
This is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely on English alone when we want to establish relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From the results of the recent examinations of this year, we can see that the languages are at the top of the charts and with the highest pass rates in the private schools.
68% of students who studied foreign languages obtained an A.
The data, compiled from the 74 schools that make up the SCIS, show that 72% of students achieved an honours degree in Mandarin, while 72% of those who studied German, 69% of those who studied French and 63% of those who studied Spanish also achieved an A.
This shows that Scottish private schools support languages and consider them key skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Today, languages are being given the same consideration as subjects such as science, technology, engineering and mathematics in private and all-round school curricula.
A survey carried out by the UK's Commission for Employment and Training in 2014 indicated that amongst employers, a lack of language skills is 17% of the reasons why employers have difficulty filling vacancies.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly essential to prepare young people for their future careers.
These skills are essential in a globalised world, as there are more job opportunities that require languages.
Regardless of the career you choose, if you learn a second language, you will have a real advantage in the future with a lifelong skill like this.
Being able to communicate directly with people in other countries will put a bilingual person directly at the head of the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 British adults in 2013, 75% did not speak any foreign language well enough to carry on a conversation, and French was the only language spoken by a double-digit percentage, in this case 15%.
That's why it's so important to invest in a language for kids today.
Knowing several languages, especially those of developing economies, provides children with more opportunities to find meaningful employment.
In Scotland, the languages of instruction differ according to the school.
Some schools focus on more classical modern languages, while others opt for languages considered more important for the UK by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the interests of your children, private schools always have several languages to choose from and specialists in this field.
Scottish private schools specialise in providing a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills they need to succeed, whatever the future holds for them.
We cannot deny that at this moment, in a global business environment, that languages remain of vital importance for the future of the country, so this must be reflected in education.
Indeed, modern languages should be considered "international communication skills".
Private schools will continue to offer this diversity and excellence to Scottish youth.
You have to do it right.
John Edwards is the headmaster of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
