"However, we do not see the corresponding response from the US", he added.
"Without trust in the United States there will be no trust in our national security and, under such circumstances, there will be no unilateral disengagement first on our part".
While Ri took up North Korean complaints about Washington's resistance to a "gradual" denuclearization under which North Korea would be rewarded as it took steps, his statement seemed important, as he did not reject unilateral denuclearization as Pyongyang had done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement made by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between a sitting US president and a North Korean leader held in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to "denuclearize" the Korean Peninsula while Trump guaranteed the security of North Korea.
North Korea has long sought a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has stated that Pyongyang must first lay down its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted relaxing tough international sanctions on North Korea.
"The United States insists on 'denuclearization first' and increases pressure through sanctions to achieve its coercive objective, and even oppose the 'declaration of the end of the war,'" Ri said.
"The perception that sanctions can bring us to our knees is an impossible dream for those who don't know us.
But the problem is that the continued sanctions sharpen our mistrust.
Ri did not mention plans for the second summit between Kim and Trump that the US leader mentioned at the United Nations earlier in the week.
However, he spoke of three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in in the past five months and added: "If the other side of this denuclearization issue was South Korea and not the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have reached a stalemate.
Still, Ri's tone was radically different from last year's speech, when he told the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable to attack the United States with North Korean missiles after "evil president" Trump called Kim "rocket man on a suicide mission".
At the UN this year, Trump, who last year threatened to totally destroy North Korea, praised Kim for his courage in taking steps to disarm, but said there was still much work to be done and that sanctions should be maintained until North Korea denuclearizes.
On Wednesday Trump said there was no deadline for that, and that it would take two years, three months or five months".
China and Russia are discussing whether the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its actions.
However, on Thursday US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council that: "Enforcement of the Security Council sanctions must continue firmly and without exception until we see complete, final and verified denuclearization".
The Security Council unanimously increased sanctions on North Korea since 2006 in an attempt to cut off funding for Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
