Harvard students are running a course on how to get enough rest.
This year, a new course at Harvard University is making all of its students sleep more in order to combat the growing macho culture of caffeinated, all-night studying.
One academic has found that students at the world's top universities often lack basic knowledge about how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, conceived the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after giving a talk on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
"At the end of the course, a young girl approached me and said, 'Why are you telling me this now, in my senior year?'
He said that no one had told him about the importance of sleep, which surprised me", she told The Telegraph.
The course, which launched for the first time this year, teaches students the basics of how getting good sleep habits helps with academic and athletic performance, as well as improves overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and the executive director of the university's health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students were experiencing significant sleep deprivation during the week.
The hour-long course involves a series of interactive tasks.
In one section is a picture of a dorm room, where students click on coffee mugs, curtains, formers and books to get information about the effects of caffeine and light and how sleep deprivation affects athletic performance, as well as the importance of having a bedtime routine.
In another section, participants are told how prolonged sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression and cancer.
A campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
"We know that it's not going to change the behavior of the students immediately.
But we believe they have a right to know this information, just as we have a right to know what the health effects are if we choose to smoke tobacco", added Professor Czeisler.
The culture of pride in staying up all night still exists, he says, adding that modern technology and the increasing pressure for students to sleep were a growing problem.
Ensuring that students get enough sleep and get good quality sleep should be a student's "secret weapon" in fighting stress, fatigue, and anxiety, she says, and even preventing weight gain, since lack of sleep puts the brain into a starvation mode, which causes the student to be hungry all the time.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian student of chemistry and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course, after attending one of his classes last year during his freshman year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to push a course across the campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to require all graduate students to complete a similar program of study before joining the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students consider setting an alarm for when they go to bed, as well as when they wake up.
