Almanac: the inventor of the Geiger counter
And now a page from our Sunday Morning almanac: September 30, 1882, 136 years ago today, and counting -- that was the day that the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger was born in Germany.
Geiger developed a method to detect and measure radioactivity, an invention that eventually led to the device known as the Geiger counter.
A pillar of science ever since, the Geiger counter has also become a staple of pop culture, as in the 1950 film "Bells of Coronado", starring those seemingly unlikely cowboy scientists Roy Rogers and Dale Evans:
Man: "What in the world is that?"
Rogers: "It's a Geiger counter, which is used to locate radioactive minerals, like uranium.
By wearing these headphones, you can hear the effects of atoms emitted by the radioactivity of minerals".
Evans: "Say, it's probably going to pop right now!"
"Hans" Geiger died in 1945, just a few days after his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that bears his name survives.
New cancer vaccine can teach immune system to "see" faulty cells
The new cancer vaccine can teach the immune system to "see" the faulty cells and kill them
The vaccine teaches the immune system to recognize the defective cells as part of the treatment
The method involves extracting immune cells from a patient, altering them in the lab.
They can see a protein that's common to many cancers and re-inject it
A trial vaccine is showing promising results in patients with a variety of cancers.
