The method involves taking immune cells from a patient, altering them in the lab so that they can "see" a protein common to several types of cancer called HER2 and then reject the cells.
Professor Jay Berzofsky of the U.S. National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, Maryland, said, "Our results indicate that we have a very promising vaccine".
