But at 6am, just as Gegard Mousasi and Rory MacDonald were about to face each other, the UK audience was stunned when Peppa Pig appeared.
Some were not impressed after spending so many hours awake waiting to see the fight.
One fan described the change to these childish drawings on Twitter as "a very bad joke".
"State regulations dictate that this content was not appropriate for 6 a.m., and so it had to be changed to children's programming", explained Dave Schwartz, Bellator's senior vice president of Marketing and Communications, when asked about the rebroadcast.
"Peppa Pig, that's what it is".
Scott Coker, president of Bellator, stated that they will take into account UK viewers in future programming.
"I think we can solve it when we think about repetition", Coker said.
"But if it's 6 a.m. there, we can't solve it until Sunday, which will be Monday for them.
But we're working on a solution.
When the change occurred, I started receiving a lot of messages, and not all of them were pleasant.
We were trying to fix it because we thought it was a technical error.
But no, it was a government problem.
I promise it won't happen again.
We're going to limit ourselves to five fights instead of six, and we wanted to give our fans as much as possible, but we're overreacting and
They give us a lot of anger".
Tom Daley felt inferior because of his sexuality
Olympic jumper Tom Daley claims he grew up feeling inferior to everyone else because of his sexuality, but this made him find the motivation to succeed.
This 24-year-old athlete claims that he didn't realize that not everyone was like him until he got to high school.
A guest on the first broadcast of Radio 4's Desert Island Discs program led by Lauren Laverne, he explained that he started speaking out about gay rights to give hope to others.
He also shared that being a father helped him to put the importance of winning the Olympics into relative perspective.
Kirsty Young, the regular host of this show, is on sick leave.
As a guest on the first Laverne-led show, Daley shared that he felt "inferior" to other people because "it wasn't socially acceptable to like boys and girls".
She also stated: "To this day, that feeling of inferiority and of being different is what has driven me and given me the strength to succeed".
I wanted to prove that I was "someone" so that people wouldn't feel disappointed when they found out about their sexuality.
With two Olympic bronze medals, he became a prominent LGBT activist and used his appearance at the Commonwealth Games in Australia to call for more countries to decriminalize homosexuality.
He decided to speak out because he felt lucky to be able to live openly and without fear of repercussions, and he wanted to give hope to others.
The three-time world champion said that falling in love with American filmmaker Dustin Lance Black, whom she met in 2013, "was a complete surprise".
Daley married this Oscar winner last year and claims that the 20-year age gap between them was never a problem.
"When you live so much in such a short time" (at only 14 years old he participated in his first Olympic Games and his father died of cancer three years later), it is difficult to find someone your age who has experienced similar ups and downs.
The couple had their first child in June, Robert Ray Black-Daley, and this birth changed Daley's outlook entirely.
"If you asked me last year, my biggest motivation would be to win a gold medal", he says.
"But now I know that there are things far more important than an Olympic gold medal.
For me, my medal is Robbie".
His son is named after his father Robert, who died in 2011 at the age of 40 from brain cancer.
Daley's father couldn't accept that he was going to die, and one of the last things he asked for from his son was tickets to London 2012, he wanted to be in the front row.
"I couldn't tell him that I wouldn't be here to take that first row", shared Daley.
"I was holding his hand when he stopped breathing, and it was at that very moment, at the moment of his death, that I realized he was not really invincible", she adds.
The following year, Daley competed in the 2012 Summer Olympics and won a bronze medal.
"At that moment I knew that this was my life's dream: to jump in front of a crowd in my country participating in the Olympic Games, there was no better feeling", she confirms.
The choice of Heather Small's Proud is also not in vain, as it is the melody that accompanied him during his preparation for the Olympics and still makes his hair stand on end.
Desert Island Discs on BBC Radio 4 on Sundays at 11:15 BST.
A Mickelson in poor shape ended up on the Ryder Cup bench this Saturday.
American Phil Mickelson will break a record on Sunday when he plays his 47th Ryder Cup match, but he will need to improve his technique so that it does not become an unfortunate event.
Mickelson, who is competing in the biennial event for the 12th time, was benched by captain Jim Furyk and was unable to participate in either the fourball or the foursomes on Saturday.
Instead of being the center of the action, as so many other times for the United States, the five-time champion spent the day cheering and working to improve his moves.
Though he was never the most accurate of players, not even at the peak of his career, at 48 he does not fit into the tight-knit Le Golf National, where the tall grass often punishes the wrong shots.
And if that wasn't enough, Mickelson faces in Sunday's ninth match the precise Francesco Molinari, winner of the British Open, who has joined Tommy Fleetwood to win all four matches this week.
If the Americans, four points down at the start of the 12 singles matches, start well, Mickelson's performance could be absolutely crucial.
Furyk trusted his man, though he couldn't say much more.
"He understood perfectly my role today, patted me on the shoulder, passed my arm, and told me that I would be ready tomorrow", Furyk shared.
"He had complete confidence in himself.
He's got a spot in the Hall of Fame and he's been a big part of the teams last week and this week.
I probably didn't think I'd play two games.
I thought I'd play more, but in the end, that's the way it is and that's the way we think it should be.
Like everybody else, he wants to be out there".
On Sunday, Mickelson will beat Nick Faldo's record for most Ryder Cup games played.
It could mark the end of his Ryder Cup career, a career that never quite matched his individual record.
Mickelson has 18 wins, 20 losses and seven draws, although Furyk claims his presence also provides intagibles for the team.
"He's a fun guy, sarcastic, with wit and likes to mess with people, he's a good guy to have on the team", he explained.
"I like to see the good the younger players had with him this week.
It's much more with a good player".
Europe's captain, Thomas Bjorn, fears the advantage will be lost.
Thomas Bjorn, the European captain, knows from experience that a considerable lead in the final day of singles in the Ryder Cup can easily turn into an uncomfortable ride.
The Great Dane made their debut in 1997 in a match at Valderrama, where a team captained by Seve Ballesteros had a five-point lead over the Americans, but ended up reaching the goal line with a minimal advantage winning 141⁄2-131⁄2.
"You still think we had a big advantage in Valderrama; just like in Brookline, where we lost, but in Valderrama we won by a little", reflects Bjorn, pictured, after seeing the 2018 promotion win 5-3 on Friday and, yesterday, 10-6 at Le Golf National.
History shows that this is not over.
Tomorrow we have to go through them all.
We have to go out there and do the right thing.
This isn't over until the points are on the scoreboard.
Our goal is to win that trophy, and we have to focus on that.
I will not tire of saying it, I am focused on our 12 players who are on our side, but I am also very aware of what is on the other side: the best players in the world".
Enchanted by the performance of his players on a hard golf course, Bjorn added: "I would never sing victory before time.
Tomorrow we face the other beast.
Tomorrow is the day of the individual performances, and we have to prove our worth there too.
It's great to have a partner by your side when things are going well, but when you're facing things on your own, then you're testing your golf skills to the limit.
That's the message you need to give the players, to bring out the best in themselves tomorrow.
Now you leave your partner behind, and he has to make the best of himself".
Unlike Bjorn, Jim Furyk will seek to have his players perform better individually than their teammates, with the exception of Jordan Spieth and Justin Thomas, who added three points from four.
Furyk himself was at both ends of those rounds on the final day, being part of the winning team in Brookline, but finishing as the loser after the European miracle in Medinah".
"I remember every damn word", he replied when asked if he remembered how Ben Crenshaw, the captain in 1999, had gathered the players for the final day.
"We have 12 big games, but you want to have a quick start like Brookline or Medinah.
When you see momentum going in one direction, there's a lot of pressure in those intermediate parts.
We've prepared our lineup with this in mind and we've put the players in the way we think we want to do tomorrow".
Thomas is tasked with trying to lead the fight and face Rory McIlroy in the first match, with Paul Casey, Justin Rose, Jon Rahm, Tommy Fleetwood and Ian Poulter, the other Europeans, in the top half of the standings.
"I decided on this order because I think it covers the whole way", explained Bjorn about his selection for the singles.
Germany's new warship postponed once again
The German Navy's newest frigate was supposed to have been delivered in 2014, to replace the old Cold War-era warships, but will not arrive until at least next year due to faulty systems and rising costs, local media reported.
The commissioning of the "Rheinland-Pfalz", the lead ship of the new Baden-Wuerttemberg-class frigates, has been postponed until the first half of 2019, according to a military spokesman to the newspaper Die Zeit.
The ship was due to be commissioned into the Navy in 2014, but post-delivery problems affected the fate of this ambitious project.
The four Baden-Württemberg-class ships, which the Navy commissioned in 2007, will replace the older Bremen-class frigates.
It is understood that they will have a powerful cannon, different anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles, as well as concealment technology, such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic signatures.
Other important features include longer maintenance periods, it should be possible to deploy newer frigates up to two years outside of the ports of origin.
However, as Die Zeit points out, these continuing delays mean that the warships with the latest technology, and which will allow Germany to project its power abroad, will be outdated when they enter service.
The ill-fated F125 frigate made headlines last year when the German Navy officially refused to commission the vessel and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
It was the first time the Navy had returned a ship to a builder after delivery.
Little was known of the reasons behind this return, but German media reported "crucial software and hardware defects" that made it impossible to use the warship in a combat mission.
The software flaws were particularly important, as the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class ships will be operated by a crew of 120 sailors; that is, half the personnel needed on the former Bremen-class frigates.
In addition, the ship was found to have a dramatic overweight, which reduces its performance and limits the Navy's ability to add upgrades in the future.
The 7,000-ton Rheinland-Pfalz is thought to weigh twice as many as the similar class of ships used by the Germans in World War II.
In addition to the faulty hardware, the total cost of the project, which includes crew training, is also becoming an issue.
It is claimed that it has already reached the staggering figure of €3100 billion, up from the initial €2200 billion.
The problems of the younger frigates are of particular importance in light of recent warnings that Germany's naval power is running out.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the German parliament's defense committee, acknowledged that the Navy is running out of ships to deploy.
The officer says that this problem is growing, as the old ships have been removed, but not replaced by new ones.
He also lamented that none of the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class frigates had been able to join the Navy.
The National Trust spies on the secret life of bats
New research being carried out on a farm in the Scottish Highlands aims to reveal how bats use the landscape to forage.
It is hoped that the findings will shed light on the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and help guide future conservation activities.
This study led by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland will follow the Pipistrellus pygmaeus and Pipistrellus pipistrellus bats, as well as the Myotis daubentonii and Plecotus auritus bats in the Inverewe gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording equipment will be placed at key locations around the property to monitor bat activities during the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also carry out mobile surveys with hand-held detectors.
An expert sound analysis of all the recordings will determine the frequency of the bats' calls and what each species is doing.
A habitat map is then drawn to create a detailed landscape-scale picture of their behaviour.
Rob Dewar, a nature conservation adviser at NTS, hopes the results show which areas of habitat are more important to bats and how each species uses them.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as creating grasslands and which is the best way to maintain forests for bats and other associated species.
Bat populations in Scotland and across the UK have declined considerably over the last century.
These animals are threatened by construction and development affecting the nest and habitat loss.
Air generators and tree-lining also pose a risk, as do glue-covered fly traps, some chemical treatments of building materials, and attacks by domestic cats.
Bats are not blind,
But because of their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when hunting.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique to locate insects and obstacles in their flight path.
NTS, which is responsible for the care of over 270 historic buildings, 38 gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes bats very seriously.
It has ten trained experts, who carry out periodic surveys, nest inspections and, on occasion, even rescues.
The organisation even has Scotland's first and only bat reserve at Threave Estate in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
David Thompson, estate manager, claims this is the ideal territory for them.
"In Threave we have a large area for bats", he says.
"We have old buildings, historic trees and a wonderful habitat.
But there's a lot we don't know about bats, so the work we're doing here and on other properties will help us better understand what they need to thrive".
He emphasizes the importance of controlling the presence of bats before undertaking maintenance tasks on properties, as it is possible that the unintentional destruction of a single mothering calf can kill up to 400 females and young, which could exterminate an entire local population.
Bats are a protected species and it is illegal to kill, harass or molest them, as well as destroy their nests.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish officer at the Bat Conservation Trust, encourages people to help:
"There is still much to learn about bats, and for many species, we don't know how their populations are doing".
Ronaldo dismisses rape claims and his lawyers are preparing to sue the German publication
Cristiano Ronaldo has called the rape allegations against him false, claiming that all people want is to be known using his name.
His lawyers are suing the German magazine Der Spiegel for publishing these allegations.
The Portugal and Juventus forward was accused of raping Kathryn Mayorga, an American woman, in a Las Vegas hotel in 2009.
The footballer allegedly paid the woman $375,000 to keep her quiet about the incident, Der Spiegel reported on Friday.
Hours after its publication, Ronaldo, 33, flagged this fake news in a live video from his Instagram account, which has 142 million followers.
"No, no, and a thousand times no.
What was said today is false", the five-time Ballon d'Or winner told the camera.
"People want to be known by my name.
It's only natural.
They want to be famous just by saying my name, it's part of my job.
I am a happy and respectable man", the player added with a smile.
Ronaldo's lawyers are preparing to sue Der Spiegel over the allegations, which they call "an inadmissible statement of suspicion in the area of privacy" according to Reuters.
Lawyer Christian Schertz said the player would seek compensation for "moral damage in an amount corresponding to the gravity of the offence, which is probably one of the most serious personal rights violations in recent years".
The alleged incident took place in June 2019 in a suite at the Palm Hotel and Casino in Las Vegas.
After meeting at a nightclub, Ronaldo and Mayorga would have returned to the player's room, where he allegedly raped her, according to documents filed in the District Court of Clark County, Nevada.
Mayorga claims that Ronaldo, after the alleged incident, bowed out saying that he was a 99 percent gentleman, but that that 1 percent had betrayed him.
The documents state that Ronaldo confirms that the two had consensual sexual relations.
Mayorga also claims that she went to the police and told them about the photos of the injuries, but later agreed to an out-of-court settlement because she was terrified of reprisals and worried about public mockery.
The 34-year-old says she's seeking to revoke the agreement as she continues to be traumatized by the alleged incident.
At the time of the alleged crime, Ronaldo was about to join Real Madrid from Manchester United, and this summer he joined Italian giants Juve in a €100 million deal.
Brexit: Car manufacturers would leave the UK
The UK would forever mourn the loss of its position as the world's leading car manufacturer after Brexit, according to business secretary Greg Clark.
He added that it was worrying that Toyota UK had stated on the BBC that if Britain left the EU without a deal, it would temporarily halt production at its Burnaston plant near Derby.
"We need to come to an agreement", Clark added.
The Japanese carmaker said that in the event of no-deal Brexit, the impact of border delays could cost jobs.
The Burnaston plant, which produces Toyota's Auris and Avensis models, produced some 150 000 vehicles last year, 90% of which were exported to the rest of the EU.
"In my view, if Britain leaves the EU at the end of March, we will witness production come to a halt at our factory", said Marvin Cooke, Toyota's general manager in Burnaston.
Other UK carmakers also expressed their fear of leaving the EU without reaching an agreement on the functioning of cross-border trade, including Honda, BMW and Jaguar Land Rover.
For example, BMW confirmed that it would close its Mini plant in Oxford a month after Brexit.
One of the main concerns of car manufacturers is the supply chain risk in the event of no Brexit deal.
Toyota's production line is very tight, every 37 minutes parts arrive from UK and EU suppliers for custom-made cars.
If the UK leaves the EU on March 29 without a deal, the border could be affected and delays and shortages of parts could result.
The company claims that it would be impossible for Toyota to maintain a normal pace for more than one day at the Derbyshire plant, so production would have to stop.
Clark claims that Theresa May's Chequers plan for future relations with the EU is "precisely calibrated to avoid such checks at the border".
"It's imperative that we have a deal and we want to have the best deal so that we can enjoy the success we have now but also make the most of this opportunity", he said on BBC Radio 4's Today programme.
"Toyota's experience and other manufacturers' experience is that you need to continue these excellent supply chains".
Toyota could not estimate how long production would stop, but warned that in the long run the added costs would reduce the plant's competitiveness and could even cost jobs.
Peter Tsouvallaris, a Burnaston employee for 24 years and Unite's union coordinator, said his members are increasingly concerned: "From experience, I know that once these jobs go away, they never come back.
A government spokesman said they had presented a precise and credible plan for the future relationship between the UK and the EU.
Trump's meeting with Rosenstein may be postponed again
The White House has said that the high-stakes meeting between Donald Trump and Deputy Attorney General Rosenstein could be delayed by another week due to the fight over Supreme Court nominee Brett Kavanaugh.
Rosenstein is overseeing the work of special counsel Robert Mueller, who is investigating Russian election interference, ties between Russian aides and Trump, and possible obstruction of justice by the president.
Whether Trump fires the deputy attorney general or not, which would jeopardize Mueller's independence, has fueled rumors in Washington for months.
Earlier this month, the New York Times reported that Rosenstein had talked about using a microphone to record conversations with Trump and the possibility of impeaching the president under the 25th Amendment.
However, Rosenstein denied the report.
But last Monday, he went to the White House amid reports that he was on the verge of resigning.
Instead, a meeting with Trump, who was in New York on Thursday, was announced.
Trump stated that he would prefer not to have to fire Rosenstein, but the meeting was delayed to avoid a clash with the Senate Judiciary Committee hearing in which Kavanaugh and Christine Blasey Ford, one of the women accusing him of sexual misconduct, testified.
On Friday, Trump ordered a week-long FBI investigation into the Kavanaugh allegations, further delaying the Senate vote.
Sarah Sanders, Trump's press secretary, was featured on Fox News Sunday.
When asked about the meeting with Rosenstein, he replied: "There is no date set yet, it could be this week or it could be delayed another week, given everything that is happening in the Supreme Court.
We'll see, but you know I like the press to be informed".
Some journalists have questioned that assertion, as Sanders has not held a press conference since September 10.
When Chris Wallace asked him why,
Sanders claimed that the lack of a news briefing was not due to an aversion to the grandiloquence of reporters, though she added that she would not be the one to deny that attitude.
He also suggested that direct contact between Trump and the press would increase.
"The president grants more interviews than the previous president", he said, though he did not cite any source that could support the data.
Briefings will continue, Sanders said, but insisted that "if the press has the opportunity to ask the president of the United States directly, that's much better than directing the questions to her.
You are witness to how we've been doing this for the last few weeks, and that will replace a press conference where you can speak directly to the president of the United States".
Trump often answers questions when he leaves the White House or participates in open sessions or press conferences with visiting dignitaries.
However, solo press conferences are rare.
Perhaps the president demonstrated the motive this week in New York, with a freewheeling and sometimes bizarre appearance before a gathering of journalists.
A letter from the Health Secretary to calm Brexit fears
The Secretary of State for Health has written a letter to EU workers in Scotland's NHS expressing the country's gratitude and its wish for them to stay in the country after Brexit.
Jeane Freeman MSP sent a letter less than six months before the UK leaves the EU.
The Scottish Government has committed to cover the cost of covered status applications for EU citizens working in its devolved public services.
In his letter, Freeman wrote: "During the summer, negotiations between the UK and the EU on leaving continued, and decisions are expected to be reached this autumn.
However, the UK government, for its part, has also stepped up its preparations for a possible no-deal situation.
I know this is a time of uncertainty for all of us.
So I want to reiterate how much I value the contribution of each of the staff members, regardless of their nationality.
Partners from the European Union and beyond, bring indisputable experience and skills that strengthen and improve the work of the health service, and benefit the patients and communities we serve.
Scotland is your home and we want you to stay here with us".
Christion Abercrombie undergoing emergency surgery after a head injury
Tennessee State Tigers linebacker Christion Abercrombie underwent emergency surgery after suffering a head injury during Saturday's 31-27 loss to the Vanderbilt Commodores, reported Mike Organ of the Tennessean.
Rod Reed, the Tennessee State coach, informed reporters that the injury occurred shortly before halftime.
Apparently, he fainted as he reached the line.
Coaches and medical staff gave him oxygen on the sideline before taking him on a stretcher for further evaluation.
A Tennessee State coach informed Chris Harris, a reporter for WSMV in Nashville, Tennessee, that Abercrombie was recovering from surgery at Vanderbilt Medical Center.
He also said there are no details yet on the type or extent of the injury, and that Tennessee State is trying to figure out when the injury occurred.
Abercrombie, a redshirt sophomore, is in his first season with Tennessee State after being transferred from Illinois.
He made five total innings on Saturday before leaving the game, which brought his total for the season to 18.
A stamp duty will apply to foreign buyers who buy property in the UK
Foreign buyers will be charged a higher stamp duty when they buy property in the UK. This extra money will be used to help the homeless under the new conservative plans.
This measure will neutralize the success of Corbyn's campaign to attract young voters.
The stamp duty increase will apply to those who do not pay taxes in the UK
The Treasury expects to raise up to 120 million pounds a year to help the homeless.
Foreign buyers will be charged a higher stamp duty when they buy property in the UK. Theresa May will announce that this extra money will be used to help homeless people.
The move will be seen as an attempt to neutralize the success of Jeremy Corbyn's campaign to attract younger voters with promises to promote more affordable housing and focus on the high-income earners.
The increase in stamp duty will apply to people and businesses who do not pay UK tax, and the money raised will go to support the Government's campaign to reduce the number of people sleeping on the street.
The surcharge, which is added to the current stamp duty, including the higher levels introduced two years ago for second homes and purchases for rent, could be as high as 3%.
The company expects the change to bring in up to £120 million a year.
Approximately 13% of new construction in London is bought by non-UK residents, which is causing prices to rise and making it more difficult for first-time home buyers to access the property market.
Many wealthy areas of the country, especially the capital, have become "ghost towns" due to the high number of foreign buyers who spend most of their time outside the country.
This new policy comes just weeks after Boris Johnson called for a cut in the estate transfer tax to help young people buy their first home.
He accused the big builders of keeping house prices high by buying land and not using it, and urged Mrs May to remove the percentage tax revenue on moderately priced houses to fix the "shame of the housing sector" that is being lived in Britain.
Mr. Corbyn has announced an attractive series of proposed housing reforms, including rent controls and a ban on rent-seeking where the tenant is not at fault.
It also wants to give councils greater powers when it comes to building new housing.
Mrs May said: "Last year I said I would dedicate my mandate to restoring the British dream: that life should be better for every new generation.
And for that, we need to fix the disastrous housing market.
Britain will always be open to anyone who wants to live, work and start a life here.
However, it is not fair that it is just as easy for those people who do not live in the UK, as well as for companies based overseas, to buy homes as it is for working British residents.
For too many people, the dream of owning a home is too far away, and the indignity of not having a roof remains too real".
Jack Ross: "My ultimate ambition is to be able to coach Scotland".
Sunderland manager Jack Ross has stated that his "ultimate ambition" is to become Scotland manager at some point.
The 42-year-old Scot is relishing the challenge of reviving the North West club, who currently sit third in League One, three points away from the top.
He arrived at the Stadium of Light this summer after leading St Mirren back to the Scottish Premiership last season.
"When I was a player, my dream was to play for my country.
I played once for the B team, and that was it", Ross told BBC Scotland's Sportsound.
"I grew up watching Scotland play in Hampden many times with my father when I was a boy, something I always wanted to relive.
But that opportunity will only come if I succeed in running a club".
Ross's predecessors as Sunderland's head coach include Dick Advocaat, David Moyes, Sam Allardyce, Martin O'Neill, Roy Keane, Gus Poyet and Paulo Di Canio. He was also the first head coach to be appointed to the post of manager of the club.
The former manager of Alloa Athletic claims he felt no unease at succeeding such well-established figures at such a large club after previously rejecting offers from Barnsley and Ipswich Town.
"Will my success at this point depend on whether I can get this club back to the Premier League?
Because the structure and facilities of the club are undoubtedly those of a Premier League club", he said.
"It's not going to be an easy task to get there, but I'll probably only consider myself a success here if I can get the club back to the Premier".
Ross has only been a coach for three years after a stint as an assistant at Dumbarton and a 15-month stint on the Hearts coaching staff.
During that period he helped Alloa recover from relegation to the third division and helped St Mirren to go from being on the verge of relegation to winning the Championship title the following season.
Ross claims to be more comfortable now than he has ever been during his playing career at Clyde, Hartlepool, Falkirk, St Mirren and Hamilton Academical.
"I was probably at a real crossroads", he recalled, about taking over the Alloa.
"I really thought that training was perfect for me, even more than playing.
It sounds weird because I didn't do badly, I made a reasonably good living and enjoyed some success.
But playing can be tough.
There's a lot of things you have to overcome every week.
I still suffer from stress and work-related stress, but I enjoy training.
I have always enjoyed training, and now that I am doing it, I feel more comfortable than ever in my adult life".
