According to one survey, the perfect time to have a pint is 5:30 on a Saturday.
The summer heat wave has increased consumption in the most struggling British pubs, but put more pressure on restaurant chains.
Pubs and bars experienced a 2.7 percent increase during July, but consumption in restaurants fell by 4.8 percent according to the figures.
Peter Martin, a member of the CGA business advisory board responsible for compiling the figures, said: "The sunny days and England's longest stay at the World Cup have resulted in a pattern in July similar to that of June, with pubs enjoying a 2.8 per cent increase in consumption, although restaurants suffered an even greater penalty.
The 1.8 percent drop in restaurant business volume during June worsened during July.
Pubs and bars specialising in drinks were the best performers with consumption increases exceeding the reductions experienced by restaurants.
Food-specialized pubs have also suffered from the sun, though not as dramatically as restaurant operators.
It seems like people just want to go out for a drink.
In controlled pubs and bars, consumption of beverages increased by 6.6 percent during the month, and consumption of food decreased by three percent".
Paul Newman, an employee of the leisure and hospitality analyst RSM, said: "These results are a continuation of the trend that has been occurring since the end of April.
The timing and impact of major social and sporting events continue to be the main factors in relation to out-of-home consumption.
Not surprisingly, restaurant groups continue to suffer, however, a 4.8 percent annual decline will prove especially painful if added to that is the continuous rise in costs.
The long, hot summer could not have come at a worse time for the restaurant business and the weather will be in charge of telling whether the moderation of temperatures experienced during August will provide the much needed breathing space for the sector".
Total sales growth in pubs and restaurants, including new openings, was 2.7 percent during July, reflecting the slowdown in brand launches.
The Coffer Peach Tracker Industry sales indicator for the UK pubs, bars and restaurants sector collects and analyses data on the performance of 47 operating groups with combined revenues of over £9 billion and is considered the benchmark for the sector.
One in five children have secret social media accounts that they hide from their parents
One in five children (some as young as 11 years old) have secret social media accounts that are hidden from their parents and teachers, according to a survey
A survey of 20,000 high school students revealed an increase in the number of "fake Insta" pages
This news has caused an increased fear of sexual content being posted.
Twenty percent of the students said they had a "main" account to show their parents.
One in five children (some as young as 11) are creating social media accounts that keep adults in the dark.
A survey of 20,000 high school students revealed a rise in the number of "fake Insta" accounts (referring to the photo-sharing social network Instagram).
This news has caused an increase in fear of sexual content being published.
