Fishing and agriculture are the main pillars of the economy of Central Sulawesi province, especially in the coastal Donggala region.
Nickel mines are also important in the province, but are concentrated mainly at Morowali on the opposite coast of Celebes.
Palu and Donggala have been affected by tsunamis several times over the past 100 years according to the Indonesian Disaster Mitigation Agency.
In 1938, a tsunami killed more than 200 people and destroyed hundreds of homes in Donggala.
A tsunami also affected the western part of Donggala in 1996, killing nine people.
Indonesia is located on the Pacific Ring of Fire of high seismic activity, so it suffers earthquakes regularly.
Here are some of the major earthquakes and tsunamis that have affected the area in recent years:
2004: A major earthquake off the west coast of Indonesia's Aceh province in northern Sumatra on 26 December triggered a tsunami that affected 14 countries, killing 226,000 people on the Indian Ocean coast, more than half in Aceh.
2005: A series of strong earthquakes hit the west coast of Sumatra in late March and early April.
Hundreds of people died on the island of Nias, off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: A 6.8 magnitude earthquake struck the southern part of Java, the most populated island in Indonesia, triggering a tsunami that devastated the southern coast, killing nearly 700 people.
2009: A 7.6 magnitude earthquake occurred near the city of Padang, the capital of West Sumatra province.
More than 1,100 people died.
2010: A 7.5-magnitude earthquake struck the Mentawai Islands, located off Sumatra, triggering a tsunami of up to 10 meters that destroyed dozens of villages and caused the deaths of approximately 300 people.
2016: A mild earthquake struck Pidie Jaya regency, located in Aceh, causing destruction and panic as people remembered the devastation caused by the deadly 2004 earthquake and tsunami.
